56//*****************************************************************************
57//
58// For direct 32-bit access to a register or memory location, use AM_REGVAL:
59// AM_REGVAL(0x1234567) |= 0xDEADBEEF;
60//
61//*****************************************************************************
62#define AM_REGVAL(x) (*((volatile uint32_t *)(x)))
63#define AM_REGVAL_FLOAT(x) (*((volatile float *)(x)))
64
65//*****************************************************************************
66//
67// AM_REGADDR()
68// One thing CMSIS does not do well natively is to provide for static register
69// address computation. The address-of operator (e.g. &periph->reg) is helpful,
70// but does run into problems, such as when attempting to cast the resulting
71// pointer to a uint32_t. The standard C macro, offsetof() can help.
72//
73// Use AM_REGADDR() for single-module peripherals.
74// Use AM_REGADDRn() for multi-module peripherals (e.g. IOM, UART).
75//
76//*****************************************************************************
77#define AM_REGADDR(periph, reg) ( periph##_BASE + offsetof(periph##_Type, reg) )
78
79#define AM_REGADDRn(periph, n, reg) ( periph##0_BASE + \
80 offsetof(periph##0_Type, reg) + \
81 (n * (periph##1_BASE - periph##0_BASE)) )
82
83//*****************************************************************************
84//
85// Critical section assembly macros
86//
87// These macros call functions that implement critical section protection using
88// inline assembly for various compilers. They are intended to be used in other
89// register macros or directly in sections of code.
90//
91// Important usage note: These macros create a local scope and therefore MUST
92// be used in pairs.
93//
94//*****************************************************************************
95#define AM_CRITICAL_BEGIN \
96 if ( 1 ) \
97 { \
98 volatile uint32_t ui32Primask_04172010; \
99 ui32Primask_04172010 = am_hal_interrupt_master_disable();
100
101#define AM_CRITICAL_END \
102 am_hal_interrupt_master_set(ui32Primask_04172010); \
103 }
104
105//*****************************************************************************
106//
107// Compiler-specific macros.
108//
109// Macros that accomplish compiler-specific tasks.
110// For example, suppression of certain compiler warnings.
111//
112//*****************************************************************************
113#if defined(__IAR_SYSTEMS_ICC__)
114/* Suppress IAR compiler warning about volatile ordering */
115#define DIAG_SUPPRESS_VOLATILE_ORDER() _Pragma("diag_suppress=Pa082")
116/* Restore IAR compiler warning to default */
117#define DIAG_DEFAULT_VOLATILE_ORDER() _Pragma("diag_default=Pa082")
118#else
119#define DIAG_SUPPRESS_VOLATILE_ORDER()
120#define DIAG_DEFAULT_VOLATILE_ORDER()
121#endif
122
123//
124// The intrinsic for IAR's CLZ instruction is different than other compilers.
125//
126#ifdef __IAR_SYSTEMS_ICC__
127#define AM_ASM_CLZ(ui32val) __CLZ(ui32val)
128#else
129#define AM_ASM_CLZ(ui32val) __builtin_clz(ui32val)
130#endif
